# React and Next.js Component Rules

- Use functional components and colocated custom hooks (`useX`) for non-trivial logic.
- Keep presentational components thin: props in, UI out. Move fetching/transform/mutation logic to hooks/services.
- Use `'use client'` only where hooks/context/browser APIs are required.
- Keep forms aligned with project stack: Tailwind + `react-hook-form`.
- Keep component and hook names explicit (`PascalCase` components, `camelCase` functions, `use*` hooks).
- Preserve existing `IComponentProps` / `I...Props` interface naming style within each feature.
- Avoid expensive re-computation in render; memoize only where profiling or clear hot-path evidence justifies it.
- Avoid creating new global providers for local concerns.
- Ensure dependency arrays in `useEffect/useMemo/useCallback` are manually audited (exhaustive-deps is disabled).
- Avoid hydration pitfalls: guard browser-only APIs with `typeof window !== 'undefined'`.
- Keep Tailwind utility usage readable; avoid long unreadable class chains when a reusable wrapper exists.
- Prefer shared wrapper components from `src/components/atoms` before adding new primitives.
